snippet.textDisplay:
The only doubt on his capability in the league were people on TV. Generally anyone who agrees probably got the same opinions from so called "expert analysts". I've said hes got great potential if he can stay healthy (but isn't that every prospect entering the league regardless of hype?) Now he's playing out of his skin and suddenly theres no limit to his potential. I've said this recently
1) Hes not the guy everyone seems to think Lebron is gonna hand the torch off to. There are superstars in the league already trying to take it from him forcefully. My pick? Giannis. Dude incrementally improved his statistics every single year he played. And this year he added range on top of it. Next year could be step backs. The league is for Giannis to control. But nobody in the media is willing to accept that.
2) Zion has some serious discrepancies in his game. Lebron came into the league with a perimeter mindset. Zion has little to no interest in that and some cases I've seen him drive the lane and make a crossover he fumbles the ball out of bounds. Hes shooting well from the foul line but his mechanics are not gonna hold up. He needs to work on his release and hopefully that will extend his game slowly towards the perimeter. And if he wants to play post heavy he needs to diversify his post shotmaking. Simple as, a right hand for instance. That would go a long way. But who knows maybe he can be the post version of James Harden? I'm a huge fan of his and the pelicans this year. (Also a duke fan) And I see great potential. Lonzo is an unsung hero in all of this utilizing his skills to involve Zion and improving his shooting form exponentially. He has all the other tools. It's time we pump the brakes on Zion. Let the process of being in the league take over. And have the conversation in a couple years.

Btw the dude should be rookie of the year.

snippet.textDisplay:
Your first chart lists players since 1970. Too it doesn't go back one more year. In Abdul-Jabbar's first 10 games, he averaged 27.8 ppg and 11.0 reb. per game;his rookie year was '69-70. When I think of the NBA, I consider the entire history of the league, not just eras. But, forgive me in this;at 63, I've been playing, watching and studying the game since age 12, so I don't show a preference to any particular era.
What Williamson is doing is considered unprecedented because of his height and size, relative to his production.
I don't get caught up in his numbers. HOW he's doing it is what I find most impressive. I don't need ESPN to assess Williamson as a player for me. I know what I see, and have seen since his junior year in high school. He ain't the greatest. He's one of the latest? But, his athleticism,relative to his size, is truly immpressive. THAT'S what never been seen in the league before.
Body-wise, Zion is built like the old Bullet great, Wes Unseld, but with far more explosive athleticism. Unseld was a 6'7" CENTER, and averaged 13.3 ppg and 16.2 rbs per game in his first 10 games. He went on to being the 2nd player in NBA history to be voted both Rookie of the Year and league MVP;Wilt Chamberlain was the first. Spencer Haywood duplicated the feat in the ABA the following season(30.0 ppg/19.5 rbs per game).
But, love the videos, and the info. Nice to see something interested enough in the complete history of the League.
